PROFESSOR: All right.

00:00:01.320 --> 00:00:03.810
So I left you at the end of
last lecture with this

00:00:03.810 --> 00:00:09.390
incredible cliffhanger I put
up on the slide, but...

00:00:09.390 --> 00:00:12.760
So let me get a running start
and let you know where we

00:00:12.760 --> 00:00:15.280
were, finish up that lecture,
and then move in to

00:00:15.280 --> 00:00:17.860
the topics for today.

00:00:17.860 --> 00:00:22.050
So as you recall, at the end of
last lecture I was talking

00:00:22.050 --> 00:00:26.250
about a particular critique
which has been offered by

00:00:26.250 --> 00:00:29.919
contemporary social
psychologists of Aristotle's

00:00:29.919 --> 00:00:31.350
moral theory.

00:00:31.350 --> 00:00:36.610
As you recall, Aristotle has a
moral theory whose fundamental

00:00:36.610 --> 00:00:41.755
notion is that of the person
with good character--the one

00:00:41.755 --> 00:00:45.700
who acts as the well-raised one,
the person with practical

00:00:45.700 --> 00:00:47.070
wisdom would act.

00:00:47.070 --> 00:00:50.162
Aristotle calls that person
the phronimos.

00:00:50.162 --> 00:00:55.120
And John Doris, in the essay
we read, gave voice to a

00:00:55.120 --> 00:00:58.850
concern which a number of
philosophers have expressed in

00:00:58.850 --> 00:01:03.060
recent years, which is the
concern that Aristotle's moral

00:01:03.060 --> 00:01:06.710
theory commits a mistake.

00:01:06.710 --> 00:01:10.120
It commits what psychologists
call the fundamental

00:01:10.120 --> 00:01:10.730
attribution error.

00:01:10.730 --> 00:01:15.080
And that's the idea that it's
character rather than

00:01:15.080 --> 00:01:18.500
circumstance that's the primary
determinant of action.

00:01:18.500 --> 00:01:24.010
And Doris adduced a number of
psychological studies that

00:01:24.010 --> 00:01:28.000
purport to show that the primary
determinant of action

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:30.870
is circumstance rather
than some standing

00:01:30.870 --> 00:01:32.490
feature of the person.

00:01:32.490 --> 00:01:35.430
So he told us the story of the
guys in the phone booth and

00:01:35.430 --> 00:01:38.605
suggested that it's a local
feature of mood that

00:01:38.605 --> 00:01:41.540
determines whether people are
likely to be helpful rather

00:01:41.540 --> 00:01:43.520
than a standing feature
of character.

00:01:43.520 --> 00:01:46.250
He told us the story of the Good
Samaritan study, again

00:01:46.250 --> 00:01:50.215
suggesting that it was
circumstance or situation that

00:01:50.215 --> 00:01:51.125
affected behavior, not

00:01:51.125 --> 00:01:52.700
standing features of character.

00:01:52.700 --> 00:01:57.865
We ourselves read and thought
about the Milgram experiments:

00:01:57.865 --> 00:02:00.550
circumstances in which people
find themselves behaving in

00:02:00.550 --> 00:02:02.640
ways that one might think
are out of character.

00:02:02.640 --> 00:02:05.860
And we talked about previously,
and we'll talk

00:02:05.860 --> 00:02:09.240
about it again, the idea of
moral luck: the idea that one

00:02:09.240 --> 00:02:11.500
may find oneself in
circumstances

00:02:11.500 --> 00:02:14.400
that lead to behavior.

00:02:14.400 --> 00:02:19.980
So there is no doubt that there
is an element of truth

00:02:19.980 --> 00:02:24.200
to the claim that circumstance
is a major

00:02:24.200 --> 00:02:27.190
contributor to behavior.

00:02:27.190 --> 00:02:32.442
It's undeniable that there are
circumstances that contribute

00:02:32.442 --> 00:02:35.830
to how it is that people act.

00:02:35.830 --> 00:02:39.375
But that strand of social
psychology that Doris is

00:02:39.375 --> 00:02:44.250
stressing is, I think, only
part of the story.

00:02:44.250 --> 00:02:48.800
So in addition to circumstance
contributing to character,

00:02:48.800 --> 00:02:53.305
there's a large body of research
in psychology known

00:02:53.305 --> 00:02:58.740
as personality psychology which
looks at a set of traits

00:02:58.740 --> 00:03:03.790
that seem to be pretty well
established in people by their

00:03:03.790 --> 00:03:05.990
first year of life.

00:03:05.990 --> 00:03:10.570
These are traits that are quite
stable over time, and

00:03:10.570 --> 00:03:15.800
that end up correlating with a
large range of other measures.

00:03:15.800 --> 00:03:19.570
These are things like openness
to new experience,

00:03:19.570 --> 00:03:23.540
conscientiousness in carrying
out responsibilities,

00:03:23.540 --> 00:03:28.520
extroversion as opposed to
introversion, agreeableness,

00:03:28.520 --> 00:03:32.030
and neuroticism: a certain
kind of anxiety.

00:03:32.030 --> 00:03:36.090
So although it is the case
that circumstance plays a

00:03:36.090 --> 00:03:40.750
major role in determining how
it is that people behave, it

00:03:40.750 --> 00:03:44.460
is also the case that there
are contributions from

00:03:44.460 --> 00:03:47.170
individual personality.

00:03:47.170 --> 00:03:53.210
And one of the most dramatic
pieces of evidence in favor of

00:03:53.210 --> 00:03:57.136
that are Walter Mischel's famous
deferred gratification

00:03:57.136 --> 00:04:00.550
studies which I'll discuss
now and then again

00:04:00.550 --> 00:04:02.910
later in the lecture.

00:04:02.910 --> 00:04:06.330
It looks like, if Mischel's
studies which involve

00:04:06.330 --> 00:04:09.440
thousands and thousands of
children are to be trusted,

00:04:09.440 --> 00:04:13.620
that the early capacity for
self-regulation or delay of

00:04:13.620 --> 00:04:17.420
gratification in the face
of temptation is highly

00:04:17.420 --> 00:04:23.500
predictive of all sorts of
things ranging from SAT scores

00:04:23.500 --> 00:04:26.670
to social relations in school.

00:04:26.670 --> 00:04:31.470
Social and cognitive functions
seem to correlate with the

00:04:31.470 --> 00:04:35.000
certain features about
early experience.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:39.280
So although it is undoubtedly
the case that the situationist

00:04:39.280 --> 00:04:43.690
critique gets something right
and it is undoubtedly a

00:04:43.690 --> 00:04:47.480
mistake to think that the sole
contribution to behavior is

00:04:47.480 --> 00:04:50.660
character, and that the features
of the environment

00:04:50.660 --> 00:04:56.170
play no role, to say that only
contribution to behavior is

00:04:56.170 --> 00:04:59.330
circumstance and that there's no
contribution on the part of

00:04:59.330 --> 00:05:03.020
the individual is, I
think, a mistake.

00:05:03.020 --> 00:05:05.580
And those of you who are
interested in looking at what

00:05:05.580 --> 00:05:09.540
those individual differences
look like in children early on

00:05:09.540 --> 00:05:13.060
may enjoy watching some of the
videos of the Mischel studies

00:05:13.060 --> 00:05:16.080
where you get to see children
sitting in front of

00:05:16.080 --> 00:05:19.080
marshmallows, looking
like this, or

00:05:19.080 --> 00:05:25.110
this, or this, or this.

