00:05:43.470 --> 00:05:48.170
So that's the closing of last
lecture, and obviously a

00:05:48.170 --> 00:05:52.450
straightforward segue way into
the topic of today's lecture

00:05:52.450 --> 00:05:57.040
which is the question in some
ways with which we began this

00:05:57.040 --> 00:06:01.050
section of the course: the
question of strategies for

00:06:01.050 --> 00:06:06.060
regulating oneself in the face
of weakness of the will.

00:06:06.060 --> 00:06:10.830
Now, what we emphasized in last
lecture was Aristotle's

00:06:10.830 --> 00:06:15.920
picture of what it takes for
someone to be virtuous.

00:06:15.920 --> 00:06:18.360
And Aristotle said that in order
to be virtuous, you need

00:06:18.360 --> 00:06:20.250
to satisfy four conditions.

00:06:20.250 --> 00:06:23.380
You need to know what's the
right thing to do, you need to

00:06:23.380 --> 00:06:26.720
decide to do that thing because
it's the right thing,

00:06:26.720 --> 00:06:30.170
you need to do so stably, and
you need to do so in a way

00:06:30.170 --> 00:06:33.440
that doesn't cut against
your inclinations.

00:06:33.440 --> 00:06:35.800
Those are the four features
that are required to be

00:06:35.800 --> 00:06:37.822
virtuous on Aristotle's
picture.

00:06:37.822 --> 00:06:42.220
And corresponding to virtue on
the other end of the spectrum,

00:06:42.220 --> 00:06:47.140
is the Aristotelian notion of
vice which is basically its

00:06:47.140 --> 00:06:48.710
exact opposite.

00:06:48.710 --> 00:06:54.150
It's a harmonious, stable,
knowledgeable, decided

00:06:54.150 --> 00:06:59.010
tendency to act in keeping with
exactly what's wrong.

00:06:59.010 --> 00:07:01.970
So the vicious person has
knowledge of what's the wrong

00:07:01.970 --> 00:07:04.830
thing to do, decides to do it
because it's the wrong thing,

00:07:04.830 --> 00:07:09.290
stably does so, and doesn't feel
any inclination to do the

00:07:09.290 --> 00:07:10.590
right thing.

00:07:10.590 --> 00:07:15.660
So those are two ends of the
Aristotelian spectrum.

00:07:15.660 --> 00:07:18.680
In fact, there are two things
which lie a bit beyond the end

00:07:18.680 --> 00:07:19.805
of the Aristotelian spectrum.

00:07:19.805 --> 00:07:23.440
As you know from you reading
guide, Aristotle also

00:07:23.440 --> 00:07:27.380
identifies the notion somewhat
akin to the state that

00:07:27.380 --> 00:07:29.830
Jonathan Shay calls
the berserk state.

00:07:29.830 --> 00:07:33.330
This is the state that Aristotle
calls bestiality, a

00:07:33.330 --> 00:07:35.080
state below virtue and vice.

00:07:35.080 --> 00:07:38.500
And he gives examples from some
of the Greek tragedies of

00:07:38.500 --> 00:07:41.116
tearing a body apart
limb from limb.

00:07:41.116 --> 00:07:45.130
So Aristotle thinks it's
possible to move out of the

00:07:45.130 --> 00:07:47.390
moral realm altogether.

00:07:47.390 --> 00:07:51.430
Vice, on the Aristotelian
picture, is still a kind of

00:07:51.430 --> 00:07:54.470
stable and predictable way
to act in the world.

00:07:54.470 --> 00:07:57.800
Bestiality lies below that.

00:07:57.800 --> 00:08:04.100
And above virtue lies this
idea of divinity: a state

00:08:04.100 --> 00:08:06.750
whereby regulating
with respect to

00:08:06.750 --> 00:08:10.170
virtue isn't even required.

00:08:10.170 --> 00:08:13.490
But the heart of the discussion
that we read in

00:08:13.490 --> 00:08:17.490
chapter seven of Aristotle's
Ethics for today concerns

00:08:17.490 --> 00:08:20.410
itself with this
range of states

00:08:20.410 --> 00:08:22.502
between virtue and vice.

00:08:22.502 --> 00:08:25.790
And Aristotle gives a really
nice taxonomy of those which I

00:08:25.790 --> 00:08:30.430
think is helpful for
understanding what it is to

00:08:30.430 --> 00:08:31.680
engage in self-regulation.

00:08:34.360 --> 00:08:36.760
I should stress that I am no
Aristotle scholar, and that

00:08:36.760 --> 00:08:39.060
what I'm providing is
a somewhat contrived

00:08:39.060 --> 00:08:39.832
reconstruction.

00:08:39.832 --> 00:08:43.400
But I think it's helpful for
getting a handle on what these

00:08:43.400 --> 00:08:45.556
distinctions amount to.

00:08:45.556 --> 00:08:49.940
So we might ask first, what
would a state look like that

00:08:49.940 --> 00:08:53.840
shares with virtue that one
has knowledge of the right

00:08:53.840 --> 00:08:57.070
thing to do, that one decides to
do it for that reason, and

00:08:57.070 --> 00:09:00.800
that one has the inclination,
but that lacks a kind of

00:09:00.800 --> 00:09:03.940
character, or logical stability,
that Aristotle

00:09:03.940 --> 00:09:07.690
takes to be a hallmark
of true virtue?

00:09:07.690 --> 00:09:10.090
That, I think, is the state
that Aristotle calls

00:09:10.090 --> 00:09:11.230
temperance.

00:09:11.230 --> 00:09:14.520
One's inclined to do the
right thing because

00:09:14.520 --> 00:09:15.440
it's the right thing.

00:09:15.440 --> 00:09:17.220
And one knows what the
right thing is.

00:09:17.220 --> 00:09:21.290
But there isn't the sort of
predictable, law-like,

00:09:21.290 --> 00:09:25.336
stability of character
that virtue requires.

00:09:25.336 --> 00:09:28.790
Corresponding to temperance,
on the other side of the

00:09:28.790 --> 00:09:33.436
scale, is what Aristotle calls
intemperance which is, in some

00:09:33.436 --> 00:09:36.650
sense, the mirror image
of temperance.

00:09:36.650 --> 00:09:40.960
Here one is simply inclined to
do the wrong thing because

00:09:40.960 --> 00:09:42.620
it's the wrong thing.

00:09:42.620 --> 00:09:48.840
But not as a hard feature of
character in the way that he

00:09:48.840 --> 00:09:52.340
gives in the case of vice,
but just as a matter of

00:09:52.340 --> 00:09:53.500
temperament.

00:09:53.500 --> 00:09:57.560
So the temperate person,
with inclination,

00:09:57.560 --> 00:09:59.230
does the right thing.

00:09:59.230 --> 00:10:00.910
They're inclined to do
the right thing and

00:10:00.910 --> 00:10:02.586
they act in that way.

00:10:02.586 --> 00:10:07.480
The intemperate person, with
inclination, does the wrong

00:10:07.480 --> 00:10:12.080
thing and feels no conflict
in the face of it.

00:10:12.080 --> 00:10:15.200
What happens if we remove
another one of the

00:10:15.200 --> 00:10:16.710
Aristotelian features?

00:10:16.710 --> 00:10:19.440
What happens if we have
knowledge of what's the right

00:10:19.440 --> 00:10:25.050
thing to do and the decision to
do the right thing, but our

00:10:25.050 --> 00:10:29.830
inclination pulls us in
the other direction?

00:10:29.830 --> 00:10:33.780
So we have made a decision to
act in keeping with what's

00:10:33.780 --> 00:10:39.180
right, at least at an abstract
level if not a concrete one,

00:10:39.180 --> 00:10:40.760
we have a sense of
what's right.

00:10:40.760 --> 00:10:44.380
Aristotle says, and I put this
approximation in front of the

00:10:44.380 --> 00:10:47.225
knowledge that "what the
continent and incontinent

00:10:47.225 --> 00:10:52.470
person have is the recognition
of the general rule, but some

00:10:52.470 --> 00:10:55.680
difficulty recognizing whether
the general rule applies in

00:10:55.680 --> 00:11:00.200
this particular case." So the
continent person has a sense

00:11:00.200 --> 00:11:05.200
of what the right thing to do
is, has made a decision to act

00:11:05.200 --> 00:11:09.510
in keeping with that, but her
inclination pulls her in

00:11:09.510 --> 00:11:11.070
another direction.

00:11:11.070 --> 00:11:14.810
She finds it difficult to avoid
the chocolate cake.

00:11:14.810 --> 00:11:18.610
She finds it difficult to get
up when her alarm rings.

00:11:18.610 --> 00:11:22.160
She finds it difficult to resist
the marshmallow in

00:11:22.160 --> 00:11:23.640
order to get the second.

00:11:23.640 --> 00:11:28.010
But somehow she contains herself
and acts against her

00:11:28.010 --> 00:11:29.592
inclination.

00:11:29.592 --> 00:11:33.276
The mirror image of the
continent person is

00:11:33.276 --> 00:11:36.332
Aristotle's incontinent
person.

00:11:36.332 --> 00:11:40.350
In terms of their decision,
they are like

00:11:40.350 --> 00:11:41.540
the continent one.

00:11:41.540 --> 00:11:46.420
They want to do the thing that
corresponds with morality.

00:11:46.420 --> 00:11:48.810
Like the continent person,
they have a sense of the

00:11:48.810 --> 00:11:51.580
general rule, a little
difficulty seeing how it

00:11:51.580 --> 00:11:53.187
applies in this particular
case.

00:11:53.187 --> 00:11:57.160
And like the continent person,
they have an inclination to go

00:11:57.160 --> 00:12:00.890
towards a pleasure which
attracts them.

00:12:00.890 --> 00:12:04.490
But unlike the continent person,
the incontinent person

00:12:04.490 --> 00:12:08.740
finds herself unable to overcome
the inclination.

00:12:08.740 --> 00:12:12.670
And so, below the line,
she acts in

00:12:12.670 --> 00:12:16.036
keeping with what's wrong.

00:12:16.036 --> 00:12:20.450
Finally, Aristotle considers
a pair of cases where the

00:12:20.450 --> 00:12:24.270
attraction to doing the wrong
thing is not a desire for a

00:12:24.270 --> 00:12:28.660
pleasure, but a desire
to avoid pain.

00:12:28.660 --> 00:12:32.980
So in some cases, one doesn't
get full credit for being

00:12:32.980 --> 00:12:37.100
continent, one doesn't resist a
pleasure, but one is willing

00:12:37.100 --> 00:12:41.470
to put up with a certain amount
of discomfort in the

00:12:41.470 --> 00:12:43.210
face of doing the right thing.

00:12:43.210 --> 00:12:46.610
Aristotle calls that resistance:
continence in the

00:12:46.610 --> 00:12:48.281
face of pain.

00:12:48.281 --> 00:12:51.980
And corresponding to that, below
the line, is softness:

00:12:51.980 --> 00:12:54.770
incontinence in the
face of pain.

00:12:54.770 --> 00:12:58.440
Doing the wrong thing because
one has given in to a certain

00:12:58.440 --> 00:13:01.254
kind of discomfort.

00:13:01.254 --> 00:13:05.210
So I put this list before you
because I think it's not

00:13:05.210 --> 00:13:10.500
completely clear on a first
read, or a second, or a third,

00:13:10.500 --> 00:13:15.870
or a fourth through Book Seven
of Aristotle's Ethics, how

00:13:15.870 --> 00:13:20.030
carefully structured Aristotle's
picture of the

00:13:20.030 --> 00:13:23.900
human soul and its strengths
and weaknesses is.

00:13:23.900 --> 00:13:27.510
But I think that if we see
it as a set of paired

00:13:27.510 --> 00:13:33.350
characteristics, each of which
lacks or has certain of the

00:13:33.350 --> 00:13:37.880
features of paradigmatic
Aristotelian virtue, then we

00:13:37.880 --> 00:13:41.300
can get a pretty clear sense
of what the Aristotelian

00:13:41.300 --> 00:13:43.290
picture looks like.

00:13:43.290 --> 00:13:47.370
And I encourage you, armed with
this framework, to go

00:13:47.370 --> 00:13:50.965
back to the text which we've
been reading over and over in

00:13:50.965 --> 00:13:54.230
this class: the text at the end
of Book One and beginning

00:13:54.230 --> 00:13:56.540
of Book Two of Aristotle's
Ethics.

00:13:56.540 --> 00:14:01.920
And try, yet again, to see what
the picture of virtue is

00:14:01.920 --> 00:14:05.200
that Aristotle is
concerned with.

00:14:05.200 --> 00:14:08.470
So what I want to do in the
